{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650465"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:11:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:11:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18403"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18403"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.15,0.12,0.04,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114255"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11121"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96255"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25781"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114255"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following locations contains the cell bodies of upper motor neurons?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thalamus","Basal ganglia","Spinal cord","Cerebellum","Primary motor cortex"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUpper motor neurons are crucial components of the motor pathway, responsible for initiating and controlling voluntary movements. They originate in a specific region of the brain and project to lower motor neurons. The cell bodies of upper motor neurons are located in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary motor cortex\u003C/strong\u003E, which is part of the frontal lobe of the brain. These neurons project their axons down through the brainstem and spinal cord to synapse with lower motor neurons, which then innervate skeletal muscles to produce movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in coordination and balance, whilst the \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasal ganglia\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in movement regulation, but neither contains upper motor neuron cell bodies. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ethalamus\u003C/strong\u003E acts as a relay station for sensory and motor signals, and the \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal cord\u003C/strong\u003E contains lower motor neurons rather than upper motor neuron cell bodies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cell bodies of upper motor neurons are located in the primary motor cortex of the brain.","Upper motor neurons originate in the brain and project to lower motor neurons in the brainstem and spinal cord."],"references":["Patton KT, Thibodeau GA. Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2018.","Hutson M, Ward A, editors. Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press; 2015.","Longo UG, Denaro V, editors. Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature; 2023.","Hughes SH. The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2022.","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95.","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. P